Here are both approaches using Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`:

**Route Registration (AppShell.xaml.cs):**
```csharp
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**ProductListPage ViewModel — navigating:**
```csharp
// Approach 1: Pass product ID as a query string
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach 2: Pass the full Product object
var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
{
    { "product", product }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

**ProductDetailsViewModel — receiving both:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId { get => _productId; set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value); }
    public Product Product { get => _product; set => SetProperty(ref _product, value); }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service if needed
        }

        // Approach 2: full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | Query string | ShellNavigationQueryParameters |
|---|---|---|
| Data type | string only | any object |
| Survives deep link | ✅ | ❌ |
| Complex data | ❌ (must serialize) | ✅ |

Use query strings for simple IDs (and when deep-link support matters). Use `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` when passing full objects to avoid redundant lookups.
